Abstract

This project is about exploring the role of race, location, and trends over time of incarceration in the United States. Manipulating data and creating ways to visualize this data will aid understanding in how to interpret the data.

Introduction

The Vera Institutes mission is to end mass incarceration. They discuss the causes of mass incarceration, criminalization and racial disparities, reducing incarceration, and the idea of dignity behind bars. In addition, they look at investing in communities and solutions as well as research. The direct stakeholders are the racial populations this dataset depicts, including White, Black, AAPI, Latinx, and Native populations. Indirect stakeholders may be members of these groups that are not incarcerated, as the data may reflect outside perspectives on these groups.

In this project, I will be looking at the incarceration rate of racial populations of ages 15 through 64. Specifically, I will be looking primarily at Black and White populations. Looking at these proportions will provide a more nuanced perspective of the reality of incarceration in this country. Additionally, I will examine incarceration rates over time to see how the country is evolving whether positively or negatively, as well as by location, looking at differences between states for populations.

Data Summary

Analyzing this data set can lead to a more nuanced understanding of the racial implications of the American incarceration system. Its important to compare different racial populations and their proportions.

  • The Black population is 0.0988 of the total population. However, they are 0.2291 of the jail population. This means that there is a significantly larger average proportion rate of Black people incarcerated than the average proportion rate they take up in the total population.
  • The white population is 0.7622 of the total population. However, they are 0.6556 of the jail population. This means that there is a lower average proportion rate of White people incarcerated than the average proportion rate they take up in the total population.

Historically, Black populations have been overpoliced in order for the oppressor population to maintain their power. This could partially explain the difference in proportions for the Black population and the White population.

Growth of the U.S. Prison Population

Summary

Have incarceration rates increased in the U.S.?

Yes, they have, there being a major increase beginning in 1980. It also begins to increase more as the years go on, only recently stopping the increase. However, this data does not increase COVID years, which have the potential to be increasing again after the events of 2020.
